### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

Angular's signals (`signal`, and `computed`) are not bound to any injection context, however `effect` as well as `toSignal` and `toObservable` are.

Thus we have to use these functions inside an `runInInjectionContext`, which is not really possible (nor wanted), when we have to create parts of an application based on another framework (or vanilla-js), but using (at least partially) some signals.
Here, we may imagine a web-component accepting signals as input, thus, requiring an `effect` but outside of any injection context.

[Currently](https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/main/packages/core/src/render3/reactivity/effect.ts#L250) the injection context is used to: 
- get a scheduler (`APP_EFFECT_SCHEDULER`)
- get optionally a DestroyRef
- get optionally a ChangeDetectorRef
- get optionally an `ErrorHandler`
 
 Thus, I think it would be great to add more options to allow `effect`s outside of any context, but defaulting on the `injector`, only if we are inside an injection context. Hence, having  `effect`s working everywhere, just like signals.

And, if we consider that developers are not "warned enough" / safe, we may add a property like: `runOutsideOfInjectionContext: boolean`.

### Proposed solution

```ts
export interface CreateEffectOptions {
  injector?: Injector;
  manualCleanup?: boolean;
  allowSignalWrites?: boolean;
  scheduler?: EffectScheduler;
}

export function effect(
  effectFn: (onCleanup: EffectCleanupRegisterFn) => void,
  { allowSignalWrites = false, manualCleanup = false, injector, scheduler }: CreateEffectOptions,
): EffectRef {
  if (isInInjectionContext()) {
    const injector = injector ?? inject(Injector);
    const destroyRef = manualCleanup ? null : injector.get(DestroyRef);

    const handle = new EffectHandle(
      scheduler ?? injector.get(APP_EFFECT_SCHEDULER),
      effectFn,
      typeof Zone === 'undefined' ? null : Zone.current,
      destroyRef,
      injector,
      allowSignalWrites,
    );

    const cdr = injector.get(ChangeDetectorRef, null, {
      optional: true,
    }) as ViewRef<unknown> | null;
    if (!cdr || !(cdr._lView[FLAGS] & LViewFlags.FirstLViewPass)) {
      handle.watcher.notify();
    } else {
      (cdr._lView[EFFECTS_TO_SCHEDULE] ??= []).push(handle.watcher.notify);
    }

    return handle;
  } else {
    return new EffectHandle(
      scheduler ?? DEFAULT_EFFECT_SCHEDULER, // NOTE => we provide a default scheduler
      effectFn,
      null,
      null,
      null,
      allowSignalWrites,
    );
  }
}
```

### Alternatives considered

provide a `watch` function like:

```ts
export function watch(
  effectFn: (onCleanup: EffectCleanupRegisterFn) => void,
  { allowSignalWrites = false }: Pick<CreateEffectOptions, 'allowSignalWrites'> = {},
): EffectRef {
  let scheduled = false;
  return createWatch(
    (onCleanup: WatchCleanupRegisterFn) => effectFn(onCleanup),
    (watch: Watch): void => {
      if (!scheduled) {
        scheduled = true;
        queueMicrotask((): void => {
          scheduled = false;
          watch.run();
        });
      }
    },
    allowSignalWrites,
  );
}
```
